        "text": "The abstractions that are made in the act of exchange find no equivalent in the sensually perceptible form of the objects of exchange. What happens is that physically completely different goods are equated in an exchange equation. The goods themselves are not equal, the exchange equates them. In the act of exchange, it is not the equality of two commodities that is created, but their equivalence. In this real abstraction, in the equivalence generated by the act of exchange, Sohn-Rethel assumes, in short, the sociogenetic foundation of the mathematical concept of equivalence."
